segments.text: It's to be sort of the heartbeat of our discipline in terms of terminology, the theory base, where we've been.
It's changed some with new postmodernism and those kinds of issues, but it's still basically the course.
I started teaching that, and I taught program evaluation, which is now turned into the AEIS accountability system for the state of Texas.
We go online for that.
And I brought the futures class here.
We had a planning course, but not a futures class, so I
initiated the first futurism class on this campus in 1975.
In other words, the future of public, of education.
Well, it's called Planning Futurism, and it's in the College of Education, but I'm offering it this semester, and there's 20 students.
We just closed it.
And they're from business, engineering, agriculture.
So it's an interdisciplinary class.
And Letha Malloy was in one of my early classes,

John Calhoun, we had on the committee, and we did one of the first futures dissertation, the first future dissertation on this campus, where we interviewed the great higher education stars who came in here for national conferences.
And she did a study on Delphi, where the universities were going in the next 25 years.
And she wound up, as you know, being a vice president at Southwest Texas State University.
But John Calhoun was on that committee.
And I'll never forget, the graduate dean at the time saw that proposal and said, what is this futurism stuff?
What are these scenarios?
And what are these cross-impact matrices things?
And we broke the new paradigm.
We created a new paradigm for new kinds of studies because the graduate dean at the time wasn't sure.
And of course, having Calhoun on the committee didn't hurt.
So these were all graduate courses.
All graduate courses.
A normal teaching assignment then was how many?
It was two courses a semester.
And you wind up in a hurry with a great number of doctoral students who have an interest that you have.
And at that time, the program wasn't as large as it is now, but it was quite healthy.
And I've always, since I've been here within the first two years, have either had somewhere between 15 and 30 students I'm chairing on doctoral committees.
Did, back to advice, did anybody give you any do's and don'ts advice?
You know, not really.
Not really.
It was just do your thing.
And Dr. Hensling, I guess, was the only one that may have said when I would ask him things.
But I can't remember anybody saying, this is what you do, this is what you don't do.
They assumed you knew that since I'd been a department head and been teaching at other universities.
But no, I'd say that was a problem.
Were there any differences that you quickly noticed between TCU, Miami, Tulsa, and A&M?
I think the inflexibility that I found here.
There we had department chairs.
There was some rotation took place.

There was more liberal thinking about interdisciplinary kinds of issues, even though at one time we'd had an interdisciplinary education doctorate, but now since it had become a department, it was pretty much a turf kind of thing.
It was more isolated than I'd seen at Miami University.
I'd been on the faculty senates at Miami, and I was on the first faculty senate at Texas A&M.
Two of us were elected from the College of Education in 1983.
And I was fortunate enough to be one of the first elected.
That was exciting, with John McDermott and all the group trying to say, what's the core knowledge going to be in our university?
How are we going to deal with such things as accrediting problems when you're forcing students to take too much liberal arts and humanities?
How are we going to become more decentralized and have more power by faculty?
rigid department structures that this university has become accustomed to.
We were able to shatter and break a lot of that, and we were really concerned about the kind of hold that the department has had on the faculty.
And that was a meaningful three years to be on that first faculty senate.
Who were the key leaders that helped produce that faculty senate?
John McDermott got a group of people together over his department, and he was very instrumental
in getting the group together.
Paul Parish was involved in that.
I was involved in it.
David Erlandson here was involved in it.
I'm trying to think of some of the others.
Old Bill Barzak was very much involved and helpful.
I'm trying to think of a lady who's now deceased that was in biochemistry.
She was very active in it.
She was one of the first really active women in the political side of the university.
But see.
Were there any obstacles you all had to overcome?
No, because we had, you know, the only obstacle we had, I guess, was just tradition, because Rutter would not consider having a faculty senate.
Williams would have, but it was just before its time.
Well, here comes our president from Rice University,
who was very open, very faculty-oriented, and Frank was very interested in the future, visioning, and didn't like committee meetings too much.
Now, this is true.
He didn't like committee meetings too much, but he was a great faculty president.
He really was faculty-oriented, and I told him that every time I saw him.
And he helped us make this faculty senate work.
So I'll always admire that man a great deal.
And who was the chief academic officer at that time?
McDonald, let's see.
Donald McDonald?
Yeah, Donald McDonald was one of the chief academics.
Because Prescott had already.
Prescott, see, is the one I was trying to mention a while ago, who came here as provost in 76 or 77 and said, I'll not promote any Aggies.
Yes, Prescott takes over and says that.
That's right, that's right.
Do you remember who the first faculty senate chairman was?
Yeah, it was John McDermott.
John McDermott.
Yeah, speaker, yeah.
And Bill Jenkins and I were sergeant at arms.
Bill later became, you know, is now provost or president at LSU.
And, oh, yeah, he was a big, healthy guy, and I wasn't any tiny guy.
And so he'd stand up in his South African accent and mine my Texas accent, and we'd say, all right, settle down, guys.
What did the deans think about the coming of the Senate?
They weren't overwhelmed by it, but yet it was exciting because they then saw, maybe with my exception, they then saw who the leaders were on campus.

Because the faculty, the first elections, I think clearly the faculty really became involved in it and elected the people they thought could best represent them in situations where they opposed the administrative structure.
And so we had some pretty vocal people and some that weren't afraid to speak out.
And it was an exciting time, exciting time.
All right, let's jump back to your career.
How long did it take to get some doctoral students for you?
First semester, I probably picked up three or four, some of McNamara's people.
Letha Malloy was one.
He'd kind of started with her.
I picked up some of his students, three or four right quick, and then I'd say within two years I had ten, and then within five years it hadn't changed much between eighteen and thirty, you know.
Normally how did, in those early years particularly, normally how did you and a graduate student become related?
Well, through my classes many times, I'd get to know students through classes, or
contacts I was beginning to make in the field, or through some literature or something I had written.
Someone would get in touch with me, want to study with me, those kinds of things.

And I have had students over the years that have come to study, come to university to study with me, and that's always been nice to have because immediately when I got here, Harold Hawkins said, I want you to

be my backup for the administrative leadership institute which used to be the old june conference that's been going on here since the turn of the century for county superintendents we used to have a summer conference here well in 83 84 dr hawkins and i with the advisory committee changed that to meet at the hilton in the fall and it's in november third week in november and i've been running that by myself since 19 oh 86 i guess and uh
So that was something I picked up.
It's a year-long planning thing, but therefore it's helped me become very visible with the Texas Association of School Administrators and build the links.
And we have a new dean come in here, you know, like Dr. Jane Conley.
First weekend she was here, I took her to the Texas Association of Texas School Board State meeting, and I enjoyed introducing her to all the power players, you know, in K-12 education.
And because our primary responsibility here, whether people agree with me or not,
is preparing future leaders for Texas and American schools.
We prepare counselors, we do clinical psychology, we do a lot of other things, but that's still our primary thrust.
We'll live and die with that.

And so, and I have her involved in ALI each year, and so she's now, with her great skills, she's now very much involved with the power players and commissioners, and pretty soon in November I'll have the commissioner here, and

uh... key players on issues like teachers supply and demand and total systemic school change and uh... it's been fun to be out on the front of that and i've got a thirty person advisory board that helped me do that now normally did a doctoral student contact you personally about your being a chairman yeah they'd contact me and say your interests are very similar to mine i'd like for you to be my chair you understand my problem being a superintendent principal and i think that uh...
where some of the other professors hadn't had any experience in public schools much, I had, and they'd come to me because I had both a scholarship and a practice.
And most of them were already in the real world.
Yeah, most of them were in the real world.

Occasionally I'd have a young one like a David Thompson or others who were tremendous scholars who wanted to do research with me, and they had not had much administrative experience, but they wound up in higher ed.
Those types wind up in higher ed.
I've got one right now, Clark Ely,
who's just been appointed Director of Planning, Research, and Evaluation for the College Station Schools.

He'd been an assistant principal, but he got involved with me and my research for about a year, and he decided he wanted to be in higher ed rather than public schools, so he's going to do that for a while and then head toward university.
Now, were most of them then part-time students?
Yeah, most of them were part-time students.
I usually have one or two around here that are full-time that we can get enough scholarship money for or assistantship money for.
And how many of them would have a dissertation topic that would end up being appropriate for them to do?
And how many would need your advice?
Well, 90% of them need my advice.
Now, I've got a young woman here on campus who's working with an agency.
She came in here this morning.
And I've been talking with her for about a year on research she's doing on campus for her job, related to her job.
And I said, hey, let's extend that into your dissertation.
So sometimes they'll come in to me with an idea, but most of the time, through our conversations, I'll help them come up with an idea for a dissertation.
Who were some of the first students of which you're most proud to claim?
Well, I guess looking back on it, Letha Malloy certainly was one that went toward the direction of higher education.
If I start digging a little bit more, John Wilson, who's superintendent of school down at Clear Creek, just been honored by NASA.
Just an outstanding school leader.
I think probably Cheryl Shake Shaft was one of my students who wound up at Hofstra as one of the leading spokeswomen for women in administration.
I can go on and on with that.
David Thompson's over at UT San Antonio.
outstanding scholar.
Superintendent-wise, Harold Rahm, superintendent of school at Belton, was one of mine.
Jim Boyle, superintendent of school at Temple, is one of my students.
Kenny Johnson, superintendent over at Bremond.
And I just don't know how many principals I have out there, but those are some of the people who've really distinguished themselves both in scholarship and
How long would it take, since they would be full-time employees, in the 70s, 80s, 90s, how long did it take an average doctoral student to do their degree?
Three years.
Oh, that's all?
Three years, because if they could come in here and spend one year with me, they could get a lot of their coursework done.
And then their research would take them about a year and a half to two years.

If they're EDD, which we started, as you know, college started EDD in about 1976 or 7, for people who could not come in regular residency but could do it in the summer times, those people usually are sometime around between three and four years because they can come in the summers and take a lot of work.
And then they come and take weekend courses.
And now with TTVN, like I'll be teaching in the fall, if they get a dissertation topic early on, they have a record of study rather than dissertation.
The scholarship is just as rigorous, but it's more of an action research as opposed to a theoretical piece.
Now, I'm assuming that these students were not typical Aggie students.
They're really not.
If you get a former student to come in here, you don't have to really worry about them understanding all the traditions of A&M and those kinds of things.
But I spent a lot of my time in class
say, hey, you're an Aggie now.
I don't care if you don't have your undergraduate here.
And I still remember your line from a commencement address you made when you said being part of the Long Maroon line.
And I've quoted that 1,000 times.
I say, you're part of the Long Maroon line by sitting in my chair in my classroom.
And I'm going to do all I can to help you understand the traditions of this university.
I want you to feel close to it like I do.
And if you just come here as a student and not really become part of the culture, you'll never really experience and really know A&M like you need to know it.
Man's Silver Taps, I talk about that.
Muster, I have them go to Muster.
And I have them try to, I've written three books, you know, Good Bull, 30 Years of Aggie Escapades that a bunch of them have read about some of the antics.
And so I enjoy doing that.
And I like to say, look, you're not mediocre anymore.
You're coming to Texas A&M to be a leader.
And sometimes maybe the GRE scores are not as high as they might be at some other university, but you're here to learn how to lead.
We want you to be a leader in this nation, not just a follower.
And if you're going to be in my class, I don't want you going out there being a follower.
And they believe me because I mean it.
What about sharing some Goodwill-type experiences that relate to graduate students in education?
All right.
There's one that I think is just priceless.
We had a student here who was beautiful in English, a graduate student from Lamar University, very naive guy, very bright.
There were three of us ran around together.
We had Dr. Lee Martin on our committee, for instance, Dr. Hubert, several others, Dr. Barton Nelson.
And here was this really bright guy from Lamar that would believe anything.
You know, we'd short sheet him and stuff like that.
We'd go on research trips, and we'd do it three times.
He never caught on.
So Norval Northcutt, who wound up, he's teaching UT now, statistics, mathematics, and so on.
We caught him early in his programs,
And we said, you've got to have complex variables, mathematics 662, in order to get a doctorate here.
Well, they never told me that.
Didn't you know that?
Norval, I don't understand that.
How did you do?
Well, I made an A. I said, well, I made a B.
But, man, it was a tough course.
But I knew I couldn't get out here without it.
Badgett said, my advisor said I didn't have to take that.
Oh, yes, you do too, Johnny.
You do too.
We called the secretary of the math department, Sherry Kovar.
Her husband was a football player at A&M.
We said, we're sending somebody up there now.
We've already told him he's got to have complex variables.
You tell him when he comes in there that he's got to have it.
He's going to come up with his degree plan.
Well, we said, Badgett?
You've got to have it.
He went crazy.
He goes running up his academic building.
He goes running up to the fourth floor, wherever mathematics was, knocks on the door, goes in.
Who says I have to have mathematics?
I barely passed freshman algebra.
How could I?
He was going crazy.
If you don't believe me, you can go in and see our department head.
He said, yeah, I'll just see him.
Well, Norval and I had sneaked into the back of the room.
We go, we start laughing.
He turns around.
I'm not going to tell you what he yelled at us.
He had on big old leather shoes.
We had on tennis shoes.
We're running around the rotunda as fast as we can run.
He's yelling and screaming at us.
We run down the steps, and everybody on that fourth floor was out wondering what was going on.
So that, complex variables.
That's in, well, I wrote that up in Good Bull, too, I think.
Because, you know, graduate students coming in don't believe anything the other students say.
You can scare them to death.
Now, the
In the early years, the typical graduate student was a native Texan.
Yes.
Male.
Male.
And I'll tell you another interesting thing.
The first group of students who came in here in the 1960s, in the 1960s, we had an African-American named Jim Johnson.
The truth of the matter is there was another Jim Johnson.
They didn't know this Jim Johnson was an African-American.
He came in by default.
And got his PhD, went and retired from Texas Southern University.
But that was a mistake at the time because there were no black students here until 67, 68, basically.
And he didn't have any problems?
No, he was great.
Great.
We'd slip up and say the wrong things occasionally.
And he'd correct us.
But I'll never forget that.
By the time you got here,
There were women.
Yes.
Yes.
Did you have any impression of how, in the department and in the college, how were the women and minorities received in the 70s?
Well, it was so unusual to see them, except we had them coming in graduate programs in the summers and those kinds of things.
They were certainly in the minority.
And we had Kamel Maghrabi, for instance, who's, I'm the first American graduate
from the PhD program in education at Texas A&M.
Wesley Summers was second.
He was former superintendent in Bryan.
But Kamel Maghrabi from Jordan was first, because he'd already been here a year.
And he transferred most of his work to education.
So we had quite a few international students, because we had to take French, Russian, or German.
Then we had to have two languages in the early PhD program.
And so it seemed to me that the acceptance of minorities
There wasn't any exclusion, but there was certainly no effort to recruit minority students that I can remember.
Some of the women were beginning to come into the programs who were heading for principalships.
Very little emphasis on superintendency.
Certainly some emphasis on higher ed.
We had some women go to higher education early on out of our programs.
But no, there wasn't much effort to recruit anybody but the white male.
And Frank Hubert's role in supporting the program?
I think without Frank Hoover, we wouldn't have had the doctoral program, even though Dr. Hensling did most of the legwork.
He had his own set way of thinking about what a doctor should be because he was so influenced by his work in government and education from the University of Texas.
Probably, he was probably, in my opinion, he probably was not field-oriented enough.
He was probably not...
as sensitive to the public schools at the time, even though he was a power player with the Coordinating Board and with the State Board of Education, with J.W.
Edgar and those kind of people.
It was really kind of the old kingdom kind of deanship.
It really was.
Now, the other major players at the doctoral level in education administration in that era statewide were whom?
Well, Larry Haskew, University of Texas.
Very, very big name.
I admired him a great deal.
He was probably the major player.
Then the schools that had the big programs
Yeah.
UT Austin, who else?
UT Austin, University of Houston had started their program.
Texas Tech had a pretty big program.
And that was it.
That was it.
Baylor didn't have theirs at the time.
TCU did not have one.
SMU.
Were you all deliberately trying to pattern yourselves after anybody else?
I think so.
The study I did pretty much said, here's what a doctoral program looks like.
So many hours, languages, so much statistics, dissertation quality, how many committees you got to have, how long it takes.
So yeah, I think the UT program influenced us a lot.
But the UT program is very similar to the most good doctoral programs around the nation in terms of
your admission process, what did you have on a GRE, and things like that.
After you got here, what was your first big publication, your first big achievement?
Got here in 75.
Probably, in terms of publications,
I had some things published in the Phi Delta Kappa, which is well read, and I had a piece published in the Education Administration Quarterly, which is kind of our flagship.
And then my first book was in 1985, co-authored with Finn McEnglish and Betty Steffi, which became sort of a
a landmark piece for Skills for Successful School Leaders, which is now the Skills for 21st Century School Leaders.
We just published it again two years ago, and it's become sort of a bestseller in our field.
A lot of articles for journals and things like that during those early years.
Do you think those publications helped attract students?
Oh, there's no question about it.
Now, I presume you all didn't do much deliberate recruitment.
No, we did not.
We did not.
But I started in having people
who had read some of my stuff encouraged their students to come to Texas A&M.
Now, in the college, by the time we got to the mid-'70s, the department, what were the other departments in the college?
They were curriculum instruction, educational psychology, the department of, I guess what we called industrial
education that was very big, you know, with Jim Boone and that bunch.
Health and physical education, now kinesiology.
And that was it.
Who were the key people in those various departments in the 70s?
In the 70s, in EDCI, I guess,
Looking back on it, Glenn Johnson, Bob Schutz, key players who were very influential in what took place.
In industrial education, Jim Boone, James Boone.
I'm trying to think.
Oh, he's retired now.
Oh, gosh, he did a lot of writing, a lot of work.
I can't think of his name.
His wife teaches at Blinn College, and he's an Aggie himself.
Kinesiology, of course, still Dr. Landis.
Carl Landis.
Carl Landis was just a legend, one of the finest scholars in kines or health and physical PE he'll ever have.
Tishler had retired by that time.
Of course,
Coming in to that department, they had Homer Tolson.
I'm trying to think, Dowell, a fellow named Dowell, D-O-W-E-L-L. And Charlie Shea was new.
But that was pretty much it.
Y'all were the only one that was graduate only.
We were the only one graduate only.
That's right.
And in terms of number of graduate students, y'all and who else was big?
EDCI?
EDCI and us were the larger programs.
At that time, health and physical education had a really good general degree for people who wanted to teach physical education at small colleges and universities.
They were pretty big at that time.
When they went strictly Kniece, more toward the scientific approach, and cut that program out, they'd become much smaller.
Dean Hubert becomes chancellor in the late 70s.
Were y'all, were faculty members aware that that was about to happen?
Not at all, because we'd been concerned about his health.
And he'd gotten out because he was just, you know, getting tired.
And the next thing I know, he was invited for a cup of coffee.
And I know that's because I'd talked with him, invited for a cup of coffee.
And he said, well, I'd like you to be our chancellor.
And I never shall forget this one.
You may or may not use this.
Dr. Miller was president.
I'd been offered a deanship.
I go over to Dr. Miller, and I say, Jarvis, is there any opportunity for me in terms of the deanship at Texas A&M?
It's the only deanship I'd even consider.
And I said, I realize when you're a homeboy, sometimes your dirty laundry and all those kinds of issues are there.
But I said, I've got a deanship offer here.
And he turned to me and he said, well, I don't know what my future is here.
He said, anytime you have a chancellor who's counting paperclips and telling you exactly what to do every day, I don't even know what my future is.
I'll never forget that.
About when was this?
That was about two or three months after he'd become chancellor, after Hubert had become chancellor.
Oh, okay.
And the friction was already there.
He said, when I've got people coming and counting my paperclips, I don't know what I'm going to do.
And I said, well, I've got a decision to make because I went through anguish.
Next thing I know, I'm on the Athletic Council.
Chuck Sampson, who was then head of the Athletic Council, later was interim president.
Marvin Tate was athletic director.
And they appointed me to the Athletic Council.
And I was on that for eight years, along with Tom Chandler.
I mean, Tom Adair, some wonderful people.
And that was a year when the Athletic Council really
in my opinion, had a lot of influence.
And when Jackie Sherrill came in, the friction started between me and him because I was chairing a blue ribbon committee on eligibility and those kinds of things.

And then after he left, then the whole tenor of the faculty senate, I mean the athletic council started changing because the faculty senate wanted to have their hand in it because they thought maybe they're,

the council wasn't tough enough on the athletic program, typical kind of thing, and I was off Dr. Boynton, Dr., I forget who the president was at the time, I guess it was Frank, appointed me, Vandiver, appointed me to two terms, then I finished out another term for somebody else, but it was a good time.
As far as you know, how did you get on the council in the first place?
I think Marvin Tate's
nominated me.
I think Dr. Miller.
He was already, Marvin was already the AD?
He was the AD, and I think a conversation with Miller and him, and then Chuck Sampson, who was chair of the council at the time, agreed.
So that Emory was already gone.
He was already gone.
Tom Wilson was the coach.
Tom Wilson was the coach.
When they fired Tom Wilson, Tom tried to call me and said, John, don't let him do this.

uh... bill romaine who's recently passed away uh... bill and i were pretty much couldn't understand why we'd bring in a million dollar coach and treat tom wilson the way the board of regents had treated him the way uh... the university treated tom wilson uh... i never have appreciated that and i asked uh... the first day we brought jackie sherrill in here we interviewed him over in msc because we were hiding didn't want anybody to see us because they didn't know he was on campus they flew up and got him uh... in a lear jet bill uh...
who's on the Board of Regents, and Jim Bond.
Billy McKenzie.
